      "title": "Variable Mass",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Variable Mass</strong></h3><p>Problems related to variable mass can be solved in following three steps&nbsp;</p><ol><li>Make a list of all the forces acting on the main mass and apply them on it.</li><li>Apply an additional thrust force ${{\\vec{F}}_{\\text{t}}}$ on the mass, the magnitude of which is $\\left| {{{\\vec{v}}}_{\\text{r}}}\\left( \\pm \\frac{\\text{dm}}{\\text{dt}} \\right) \\right|$ and direction is given by the direction of ${{\\vec{v}}_{\\text{r}}}$ in case the mass is increasing and otherwise the direction of $-{{\\vec{v}}_{\\text{r}}}$ if it is decreasing.</li><li>Find net force on the mass and apply ${{\\vec{F}}_{\\text{net }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }}}=\\text{m}\\frac{\\overrightarrow{\\text{dv}}}{\\text{dt}}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }(\\text{m}=$ mass at that particular instant $)$</li></ol><p><strong>Rocket Propulsion&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Consider the powered flight of a rocket vehicle. Assuming the following :</p><ol><li>The rocket may have an initial velocity</li><li>The rocket is initially unpowered.</li><li>Gravity is negligible.</li><li>The propellant mass flow rate is constant.</li><li>The exhaust velocity relative to the rocket is constant.</li></ol><p>A diagram of the rocket is shown for two time cases in Figure.</p><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"333\" height=\"110\"></p><p>$\\text{u},\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ m}$</p><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"333\" height=\"113\"></p><p>Note that</p><p>$\\mathrm{v}=$ absolute rocket velocity</p><p>$\\mathrm{u}=$ absolute exhaust gas velocity</p><p>$\\mathrm{m}=$ mass</p><p>The initial momentum of the system ${{\\text{P}}_{\\text{i}}}$ is</p><p>${{\\text{P}}_{\\text{i}}}=\\text{mv}$ (1)</p><p>The final momentum of the system ${{\\text{P}}_{\\text{f}}}$ is</p><p>${{\\text{P}}_{\\text{f}}}=\\left( \\text{m}-\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ m} \\right)\\left( \\text{v}+\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ v} \\right)+\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ m}u$ (2)</p><p>The change in momentum $\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ P}$ is</p><p>$\\Delta \\mathrm{P}=\\mathrm{P}_{\\mathrm{f}}-\\mathrm{P}_{\\mathrm{i}}$ (3)</p><p>$\\Delta \\mathrm{P}=[(\\mathrm{m}-\\Delta \\mathrm{m})(\\mathrm{v}+\\Delta \\mathrm{v})+\\Delta \\mathrm{m} \\mathrm{u}]-\\mathrm{mv}$ (4)</p><p>$\\Delta \\mathrm{P}=\\mathrm{mv}+\\mathrm{m} \\Delta \\mathrm{v}-\\mathrm{m} \\Delta \\mathrm{v}-\\Delta \\mathrm{m} \\Delta \\mathrm{v}+\\Delta \\mathrm{mu}-\\mathrm{mv}$ (5)</p><p>$\\Delta \\mathrm{P}=\\mathrm{m} \\Delta \\mathrm{v}-\\mathrm{v} \\Delta \\mathrm{m}-\\Delta \\mathrm{m} \\Delta \\mathrm{v}+\\Delta \\mathrm{mu}$ (6)</p><p>$\\Delta \\mathrm{P}=[\\mathrm{u}-(\\mathrm{v}+\\Delta \\mathrm{v})] \\Delta \\mathrm{m}+\\mathrm{m} \\Delta \\mathrm{v}$ (7)</p><p>Let $\\text{c}$ be the exhaust gas velocity relative to the rocket. Recall that $\\text{c}$ is assumed to be constant.</p><p>$\\text{c}=\\left[ \\text{u}-\\left( \\text{v}+\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ v} \\right) \\right]$ (8)</p><p>Substitute equation (8) into (7).</p><p>$\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ P}=\\text{c }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ m}+\\text{m }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ v}$ (9)</p><p>The change in momentum with respect to time is</p><p>$\\frac{\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ P}}{\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ t}}=\\text{c}\\frac{\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ m}}{\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ t}}+\\text{m}\\frac{\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ v}}{\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ t}}$ (10)</p><p>Take the limit as the time interval approaches zero.</p><p>$\\frac{dP}{dt}=c\\frac{dm}{dt}+m\\frac{dv}{dt}$ (11)</p><p>Now let $\\text{F}$ be an external force applied to the system. Newton's second law is</p><p>$\\text{F}=\\frac{\\text{d}P}{\\text{dt}}$ (12)</p><p>The external force applied to the rocket is zero, however. The thrust is generated internally. Thus</p><p>$\\frac{\\text{dP}}{\\text{dt}}=0$ (13)</p><p>Substitute equation (11) into (13)</p><p>$\\mathrm{c} \\frac{\\mathrm{dm}}{\\mathrm{dt}}+\\mathrm{m} \\frac{\\mathrm{dv}}{\\mathrm{dt}}=0$</p><p>$\\mathrm{c} \\frac{\\mathrm{dm}}{\\mathrm{dt}}-\\mathrm{m} \\frac{\\mathrm{dv}}{\\mathrm{dt}}$ (2)</p><p>Equation (2) governs the flight of the rocket.</p><p>Now solve for the final velocity. Multiply through by $\\text{dt}$.</p><p>$c d m=-m d v$</p><p>$-c \\frac{d m}{m}=d v$</p><p>$\\mathrm{dv}=-\\mathrm{c} \\frac{\\mathrm{dm}}{\\mathrm{m}}$ (3)</p><p>Let</p><p>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{l}} {} &amp; {{\\text{m}}_{0}}=\\text{ initial }\\text{ rocket }\\text{ mass } \\\\ {} &amp; {{\\text{m}}_{\\text{f}}}=\\text{ final }\\text{ rocket }\\text{ mass } \\\\ {} &amp; {{\\text{v}}_{0}}=\\text{ initial }\\text{ rocket }\\text{ velocity } \\\\ {} &amp; {{\\text{v}}_{\\text{f}}}=\\text{ final }\\text{ rocket }\\text{ velocity } \\\\ \\end{array}$</p><p>Integrate equation (3)</p><p>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{r}} {} &amp; ~\\mathop{\\int }_{{{v}_{0}}}^{{{v}_{f}}}dv=-\\mathop{\\int }_{{{m}_{0}}}^{{{m}_{f}}}c\\frac{dm}{m} \\\\ {} &amp; {{v}_{f}}-{{v}_{0}}=-cln\\left( m \\right)\\mid \\begin{matrix} {{m}_{f}} \\\\ {{m}_{0}} \\\\ \\end{matrix} \\\\ \\end{array}$</p><p>The final velocity is</p><p>${{\\text{v}}_{\\text{f}}}=\\text{cln}\\left( \\frac{{{\\text{m}}_{0}}}{\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{m}}_{\\text{f}}}} \\right)+{{\\text{v}}_{0}}$</p>",
      "position": 0,
      "qcConcept": "66a0db26c03b9dcaf1afe05e"
    }
